data.content:
Here are the improved MSTest assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0) →
    CollectionAssert.That.IsNotEmpty(users);
    // or simply:
    Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count);

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive)) →
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive)); // no built-in predicate version

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3) →
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null) →
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key MSTest replacements:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x == y)` | `Assert.AreEqual(x, y)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Contains(x))` | `CollectionAssert.Contains(list, x)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(count == n)` | `Assert.AreEqual(n, count)` |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — same items, any order
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same items, same order
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)`
- `CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset)`

The main benefit: when tests fail, these give descriptive messages (e.g., "Expected: 3, Actual: 0") instead of just "Assert.IsTrue failed."
